Here is a simple C++ program that reads binary data from a file and displays it on the console:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

using namespace std;

// Function to read binary data from a file
void readBinaryData(const string& filename) {
    ifstream file(filename, ios::binary);
    if (!file) {
        cout << "Error: Unable to open file " << filename << endl;
        return;
    }

    char buffer[1024];
    while (file.read(buffer, 1024)) {
        for (int i = 0; i < 1024; i++) {
            if (buffer[i] == '\0') {
                break;
            }
            cout << static_cast<int>(buffer[i]) << " ";
        }
        cout << endl;
    }

    if (file.fail()) {
        cout << "Error: Unable to read from file " << filename << endl;
    }

    file.close();
}

int main() {
    string filename = "binary_data.bin";
    readBinaryData(filename);
    return 0;
}
```

This program defines a function `readBinaryData` that takes a filename as a parameter and reads binary data from the file. The function uses an `ifstream` object to open the file in binary mode. It then reads the file in chunks of 1024 bytes at a time using the `read` function. Each chunk is then displayed on the console by iterating over the bytes and converting each byte to an integer using the `static_cast` function.

The program also includes error handling to handle cases where the file cannot be opened or read. If an error occurs, the program displays an error message and returns.

In the `main` function, the program calls the `readBinaryData` function with the filename "binary_data.bin". This filename should be replaced with the actual name of the binary file that you want to read.

This program assumes that the binary file contains numeric values that are stored in binary form. The program reads the binary data in chunks and displays it on the console in a human-readable format. The program also handles any errors that may occur during the reading process, such as reading beyond the end of the file or encountering corrupt data.

Here is a Pascal program that implements the bubble sort algorithm to sort a list of records containing student names and their corresponding grades:

```pascal
program BubbleSort;

type
    StudentRecord = record
        Name: string;
        Grade: integer;
    end;

var
    n: integer;
    students: array of StudentRecord;
    i, j: integer;
    temp: StudentRecord;
    choice: char;

begin
    Write('Enter the number of students: ');
    readln(n);

    SetLength(students, n);

    for i := 0 to n - 1 do
    begin
        Write('Enter student name: ');
        readln(students[i].Name);
        Write('Enter student grade: ');
        read(students[i].Grade);
    end;

    Write('Do you want to sort in ascending (A) or descending (D) order? ');
    readln(choice);

    if choice = 'A' then
    begin
        for i := 0 to n - 1 do
        begin
            for j := 0 to n - i - 1 do
            begin
                if students[j].Grade > students[j + 1].Grade then
                begin
                    temp := students[j];
                    students[j] := students[j + 1];
                    students[j + 1] := temp;
                end;
            end;
        end;

        for i := 0 to n - 1 do
        begin
            Write(students[i].Name,'- ', students[i].Grade,'');
        end;
    end
    else if choice = 'D' then
    begin
        for i := 0 to n - 1 do
        begin
            for j := 0 to n - i - 1 do
            begin
                if students[j].Grade < students[j + 1].Grade then
                begin
                    temp := students[j];
                    students[j] := students[j + 1];
                    students[j + 1] := temp;
                end;
            end;
        end;

        for i := 0 to n - 1 do
        begin
            Write(students[i].Name,'- ', students[i].Grade,'');
        end;
    end
    else
    begin
        Write('Invalid choice. Please enter A or D.');
    end;
end.
